<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EscapeesCaught 1stLd-Writethru a0794 07-10 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Escapees Caught, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0794,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Two Fugitives From June Prison Escape Apprehended In Mexico</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to recast, adding that two also facing
state charges, background on Hall's return to Kentucky, other
detail, picking up 7th graf pvs, `However, police...'. ADDS two
grafs on end with background on couple killed during escape.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last two fugitives among eight inmates
who escaped from the Kentucky State Penitentiary last month were
apprehended at a hotel in Juarez, Mexico, on Sunday, the FBI said.
   James Blanton, 29, and Derek Quintero, 26, were arrested without
incident by heavily armed Mexican police in their room at the Sante
Fe Hotel around 1 p.m., FBI agent Gary Webb said.
   After being returned to the United States, the two were being
held at the El Paso County Detention Facility on Sunday afternoon
on federal charges of unlawful flight to avoid confinement, Webb
said. They also face Kentucky state charges of second-degree escape.
   Blanton was serving a 48-year sentence for murder and Quintero
was serving 37 years for robbery and kidnapping. They were the last
to be captured of eight who sawed their way out of the Eddyville,
Ky., prison June 16.
   Last Wednesday, fellow escapee Billy Hall, 25, of Paducah, Ky.,
was arrested by FBI agents inside an El Paso Western Union office.
Hall, serving 23 years for burglary and assault, waived extradition
to Kentucky and returned to the prison in Eddyville on Saturday.
   At the time of his arrest, Hall was carrying some scraps of
paper that mentioned the Mexican hotel, Webb said, and the
information was turned over to Mexican authorities. In addition, a
couple who saw news stories about Hall's capture reported sighting
the other two fugitives at the hotel, the FBI said.
   However, police and the military in Mexico were involved in
elections and could not act on the information until Sunday, Webb
said.
   After they took the two into custody, Mexican authorities turned
them over to U.S. authorities as undesirable aliens, Webb said.
   Blanton and Quintero were to appear in court on Monday.
Extradition would be worked out between authorities in Texas and
Kentucky, Webb said.
   Hall has been indicted and warrants have been issued against
Blanton and Quintero in the shooting deaths of Buford Vester Jr.,
71, and his wife, Myrtle Estelle Vester, 69, shortly after the
escape. Their bodies were found in their home near Dover, Tenn.,
about 50 miles south of the prison.
   The couple's car, with a 20-gauge shotgun inside, was found the
next day about 150 miles away in Memphis.
</TEXT>
