<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SlainAttache     07-10 0131</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Slain Attache,0134</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Classmates Pay Tribute To Slain Naval Attache</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CENTURIA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Centuria High School's tiny
class of 1954 were among about 200 people attending a memorial
service Saturday for Navy Capt. William E. Nordeen, victim of a
terrorist bombing in Greece.
   Nordeen, 51, a military attache at the U.S. Embassy in Athens,
was killed June 28 when a bomb destroyed his car. A leftist
organization called November 17 said it was responsible.
   He was buried Wednesday at Arlington National Cemetery.
   Those attending Saturday's 40-minute memorial service included
Nordeen's mother, Edna Capello, his sister Carla Anderson, both of
Centuria, and most of the 15 students who graduated in his high
school class 34 years ago.
   Centuria is a town of about 700 people in northwestern Wisconsin.
</TEXT>
