<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Britain     07-10 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Britain,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leaders Say Arms Sale To Saudis Threatens Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assoiated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli leaders Sunday said Britain's
multibillion-dollar weapons deal with Saudi Arabia threatens
Israel's security and is a dangerous escalation of the arms race in
the Middle East.
   Army generals said the deal will enable the Saudis to launch a
pre-emptive strike against the Jewish state.
   Britain announced Friday it signed a $17 billion arms deal with
Saudi Arabia, supplanting the United States as the major arms
supplier to the oil-rich kingdom. The sale includes fighter planes
and helicopters.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's aide, Yossi Ben-Aharon, said the
sale will allow Saudi Arabia to ``hit us in the soft underbelly
from the south, using the long arm it is now acquiring.''
   ``The British government is saying it has improved relations
with Israel, but we are not seeing it in any way on the ground.
This staggering sale of arms points in a different direction
altogether,'' Ben-Aharon told Israel radio.
   A statement published by the Foreign Ministry said the supply of
weapons ``of an offensive nature to countries that are in a state
of war with Israel does not contribute to stablity in the region.''
   British officials said the deal included the sale of 50 to 60
Hawk jet training aircraft, six mine sweepers for use in the
Persian Gulf, 90 helicopters, about 50 Tornado fighter planes, and
weapons systems about which they did not elaborate.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said the deal was part of ``an
escalation of the arms race by most of the Arab countries.'' He
added that it was an offshoot of the nearly 8-year-old Iran-Iraq
war, ``which gave a real push to the arms race in this region.''
   Rabin, speaking to 100 American rabbis, said Israel was also
concerned about long-range surface-to-surface missiles supplied
recently to Syria, as well as nerve gas and other chemical weapons
he said were in the arsenals of three or four Arab countries. He
did not name the countries.
   ``If our deterrents will prove insufficient,'' the defense
minister said Israel would make every effort to confront such
threats.
   Maj. Gen. Avigdor Ben Gal, a commander of Israel's forces in the
1982 Lebanon invasion, said the new Saudi weapons would make the
kingdom capable of launching ``a pre-emptive aerial attack against
Israel in case of war.''
   Other Israeli officials charged Britain with conducting an
imbalanced policy in the Middle East by selling weapons to Saudi
Arabia, while refusing to sell arms to Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
