<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-88 1153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Convention-Media Bjt   07-10 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convention-Media, Bjt,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Hope Hollywood-Style Convention Coverage Wins Over
Viewers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They may have been not ready for prime time in
1984, but this year the Democrats hope to package their convention
as a fast-paced, dramatic program that will prove irresistible to
TV networks and viewers.
   ``It takes a special kind of viewer to sit through hours and
hours of C-SPAN,'' said party spokesman Mike McCurry, referring to
the cable public affairs network that will be broadcasting
gavel-to-gavel coverage of next week's convention.
   With the three television networks scheduling only two to three
hours of convention coverage each evening, organizers are thinking
more along the lines of the people who watch ``Miami Vice.''
   ``We're trying to capture the mood and the spirit of the party
in a fairly dramatic and appealing way, short of `Entertainment
Tonight,''' McCurry said.
   Planners are weighing details ranging from who will sing ``The
Star Spangled Banner'' each night to how to fit the Boston Pops
into the convention program. Michael Dukakis, the nominee-to-be,
asked that the orchestra be included; his father-in-law is an
associate conductor.
   Videotaped visual aids, stirring music, futuristic decor _ all
are being coordinated by a Hollywood company determined to produce
a convention that leavens speeches with entertainment and elicits
an emotional reaction from viewers.
   Given the networks' short shrift and the average viewer's
attention span, most speeches are being limited to two to 10
minutes. ``It's certainly less time than most senators and members
of Congress are used to being asked to speak for,'' McCurry said.
   Whether the politicians can or will play by the rules is
unforseeable, but organizers are planning a few practical ways to
keep things moving. Among the precautionary measures: a cadre of
speechwriters available to trim upcoming speeches if the program
falls behind schedule.
   The objective is to avoid the type of snafu that forced Dukakis
out of prime time in 1984, the first year the three networks passed
up gavel-to-gavel coverage in favor of an abbreviated approach.
   Dukakis, as head of the platform committee, was tapped to
deliver the issues document to the convention. Between speech
overruns, general disorganization and a commitment to put Jesse
Jackson in prime time, the Massachusetts governor ended up on the
air just as prime time ended at 11 p.m. Eastern time.
   Speech-cutters, TelePrompter experts and other coaches will be
located this year in rooms beneath the huge podium, a complex
McCurry described as ``where we make sausage.'' Speakers will be
able to go over their remarks, receive help in honing them and get
coaching if they need it.
   Critical to the message communicated by Dukakis and the
Democrats are the 13,500 news people expected to attend the
convention _ nearly three times the number of delegates who will be
there.
   ``We marry each other for this one week of wildness,'' McCurry
said of the party and the press. ``But it's a marriage of
convenience only.''
   Typical of the temporary intimacy is a joint venture by the
Democratic National Committee and the Presidential Campaign Hotline.
   The hotline, a daily media operation during the primary season,
plans an hourly update of schedules, hot tips, news accounts and
messages from the Dukakis and Bush campaigns available to
subscribers with computer modems.
   The hotline boasts a wide network of sources among delegates and
media organizations, as well as official campaign and party
organizations. ``Information is power at the convention,'' says Bob
Balkin, a hotline editor.
   The party agrees. That's why, along with their hotline tips,
subscribers will get the DNC's ``Party Line,'' a compendium of
schedule changes, speech texts, press releases and other
propaganda, as McCurry calls it.
   ``A convention is a crazy merry-go-round ... and it's driven by
the flow of news and events and rumors,'' the spokesman said.
``We'd rather be on the merry-go-round than standing around
watching it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
