<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-88 1216EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-WisconsinSenate Bjt   07-10 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wisconsin Senate, Bjt,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money A Big Issue In Race For Proxmire Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR L. SRB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat William Proxmire used to win
re-election to the U.S. Senate while spending pocket change _
$145.10 in 1982 _ but now that he's retiring big spending has
emerged as a major issue in the campaign to replace him.
   The money issue ballooned after multimillionaire retailing heir
Herbert Kohl entered the Democratic primary, which takes place
Sept. 13.
   And while his opponents say Kohl's spending will insult
Wisconsin voters and go against tradition, polls suggest the
opposite.
   Kohl's primary election rivals, including former Gov. Anthony S.
Earl and former National Football League players union
representative Edward R. Garvey, have denounced his heavy
investment in television ads, claiming he is attempting to buy the
Senate seat.
   ``To suggest the people of Wisconsin can be bought is not
something that I have ever considered,'' said Kohl, 53, owner of
the Milwaukee Bucks of the National Basketball Association.
   Proxmire, 72, won his seat in a 1957 special election to replace
right-wing Republican Sen. Joseph McCarthy, who had died. Proxmire
became known as a sharp critic of government waste and won
re-election with frugal spending.
   In 1982, Proxmire reported he spent $145.10, down from $177.75
in 1976.
   Kohl has put nearly $500,000 into television ads since his June
1 entry, according to a survey of TV stations in five cities.
   One of Kohl's opponents, Rep. Jim Moody, D-Wis., bowed out last
week, saying he couldn't compete and would instead seek re-election
to the House.
   ``Money is now determining this Senate race,'' Moody said.
   Kohl, who was chairman of the state Democratic Party in 1977,
said he must invest in television ads to compete effectively
because it is his first bid for public office, unlike his seasoned
opponents, Earl, Garvey and Secretary of State Douglas La Follette.
   Kohl's campaign has provoked complaints from Garvey, Earl and La
Follette, who contend he should campaign in the ``Wisconsin
tradition'' and join his rivals in debates on the issues. Earl was
expected to start running radio ads stressing that argument.
   ``I think what is happening is really insulting to the voters of
Wisconsin,'' said Garvey, who led the NFL players out on strike
1982. ``I'm trying to run a campaign Wisconsin-style.''
   But after Kohl's commercials started, a poll conducted in late
June by The Milwaukee Journal found him with 28 percent support,
just behind Earl's 31 percent and well ahead of Moody and Garvey,
each of whom had 12 percent. La Follette was last with 8 percent.
The poll's margin of error was 6 percent.
   Kohl was only at 8 percent in an earlier poll, before his TV ads
started.
   ``In my 30 years in the Senate, I have never seen anything like
it,'' Proxmire said of Kohl's sudden rise. ``Money is important, of
course, and Herb Kohl's got it to spend.''
   Garvey, who has also served as the state's deputy attorney
general, said his campaign has raised about $350,000 and he has
spent all but about $80,000.
   Earl, who was governor in 1983-87, recently asked Kohl and
others to agree to a campaign spending limit of about $1 million, a
proposal Kohl rejected.
   The Democratic primary winner will likely square off against
either state Sen. Susan Engeleiter or Stephen B. King, a
businessman and former chairman of the Republican Party of
Wisconsin.
   Engeleiter, 36, first elected to the Legislature at age 22 in
1974, has served as Senate minority leader since 1985.
   King, a former FBI agent, was hired by the committee to re-elect
President Richard Nixon in 1972 to handle security. He also served
as a personal bodyguard for former Attorney General John Mitchell
and his wife, Martha.
   Mrs. Mitchell wrote a book in which she accused King of tying
her down and drugging her in order to keep her quiet when the
Watergate scandal surfaced. Mitchell said in March that King had
been given a ``bum rap'' and said his wife, who died in 1976, had a
``severe drinking problem.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
