<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Armenia     07-10 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Radio Says Factories, Transport Working Again in Armenia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transport and factory workers went back to work in
Armenia's capital Sunday, state-run Radio Moscow reported, and a
general strike sparked by a bitter territorial dispute appeared to
be winding down.
   In Moscow, Armenian activists gathered to protest the crushing
of an Armenian demonstration last week.
   Armenian activists called for the work stoppage July 4 over
apparent dissatisfaction that a recent national Communist Party
conference did not resolve the status of the Nagorno-Karabakh
region of Azerbaijan.
   The government of the mainly Armenian district has voted to pull
out of Azerbaijan and join Armenia. Armenia has backed the demand,
but Azerbaijan has rejected it, and both Armenia and
Nagorno-Karabakh have asked Moscow to intervene.
   In a Sunday report from Armenia's capital of Yerevan, Radio
Moscow said, ``There were no violations of public order and public
transport, including railways, functioned normally. More than 60
plants worked.''
   An Armenian broadcast journalist contacted by telephone from
Moscow said Friday about half of Yerevan's public transport had
resumed work that day, and the Sotsialisticheskaya Industriya
newspaper said that food-proceesing plants had reopened for
business.
   The paper said each day of the strike caused a loss of $16
million in industrial production.
   Radio Moscow gave no news of the status of a similar strike in
Nagorno-Karabakh, and it was not immediately possible to contact
the Caucasus Mountain region by telephone.
   The labor daily Trud has said that the strike in Stepanakert,
Nagorno-Karabakh's capital, has already cost $64 million in lost
industrial production. The newspaper said Stepanakert enterprises
failed to deliver $32 million worth of supplies.
   About 300 Armenians held a rally in Moscow on Sunday to protest
the crushing of a protest at Yerevan's Zvartnots Airport last week.
Demonstrators overran the airport on July 4-5, and Armenian
officials said one was killed by a plastic bullet fired by Soviet
troops who were sent to restore order.
   Armenian activists have claimed that as many as five people were
killed when soldiers fired on the protesters.
   Soviet officials denied the allegations.
   Witnesses to the Sunday rally, which was held outside Moscow's
Armenian church, said Armenians circulated photographs they said
showed the funerals of two of the people who died in the airport
protest, including one who reportedly had a heart attack while
arguing with soldiers.
   In February, ethnic violence between Armenians and Azerbaijanis
left at least 32 people dead in the city of Sumgait in Azerbaijan.
</TEXT>
