<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PeaceWalker 1stLd-Writethru   07-10 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peace Walker, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0695,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Activist to Walk 1,000 Miles for Peace</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, ``Before leaving ...'' with peace group
announcing two members will join departure; pickup last graf,
``Freedom and ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When he sets off on foot for Belgium from
Warsaw on Monday, a British peace activist and former Roman
Catholic priest will wear a sweatshirt with the phrase ``one
world'' written in five languages.
   That is the message Bruce Kent plans to spread to citizens of
Eastern and Western Europe during a 45-day hike through Poland,
East Germany, West Germany and Belgium.
   ``My main purpose is to get across the message that Europe could
live without the two military blocs and without confrontation,''
said Kent, 59.
   But the arrival of Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev in Warsaw on
Monday has set Kent scouting for alternative departure points in
case police block Warsaw roads for security purposes.
   The lawyer says he chose to start his march for a conflict-free
Europe in Warsaw and end it in the Belgian capital of Brussels for
symbolic reasons.
   Warsaw was the site of the signing of the Warsaw Pact treaty in
1955 and Brussels is the administrative center for the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   The United Nations' Association, the War on Want and the British
Campaign for Nuclear Disarmanent have sponsored the trip, Kent's
second long trek.
   He walked 500 miles from a nuclear submarine base in Scotland to
a nuclear bomb plant in Reading, England in 1987.
   That march raised $255,000 for peace causes. He has collected
$27,200 this time, enough to pay for the trip, which will cover
about 1,000 miles.
   This time, two translators and an assistant will accompany Kent.
He plans to walk six days a week and attend church services Sunday.
   Kent hopes to walk through the East German city of Dresden,
largely destroyed by British and U.S. bombs in 1945, and the West
German city of Nuremberg, where the allies tried Nazi war criminals
after World War II.
   On Sunday, the banned peace group Freedom and Peace announced
two of its members will join Kent for the departure with a banner
demanding the release of the 15 conscientious objectors the group
says are imprisoned for resisting the draft.
   Freedom and Peace has campaigned for alternate civilian service
for the military draft.
</TEXT>
