<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Manheim     07-10 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Manheim,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio And Television Writer Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emmanuel ``Mannie'' Manheim, a radio
and television writer for Groucho Marx, Frank Sinatra and Art
Linkletter, has died at age 90.
   Manheim died at Santa Monica Hospital on June 26, family and
friends said. The cause of death was not released and no funeral
services were scheduled.
   Manheim came to Hollywood in the mid-1930s from Syracuse, N.Y.,
for a brief vacation, but stayed at the behest of a friend,
composer Harold Arlen.
   Over the next 50 years, Manheim wrote for some of the most
popular radio and television shows, including ``You Bet Your
Life,''``People Are Funny,''``The Real McCoys,''``The Donna Reed
Show,'' and ``My Three Sons.''
   Manheim got his start by writing a radio sketch for Groucho and
Chico Marx for radio; Groucho Marx once credited Manheim with
helping him launch his television career on the strength of
Manheim's ``You Bet Your Life'' scripts.
   Manheim also wrote for Edgar Bergen, Rudy Vallee, Jackie
Gleason, Al Jolson, Bob Hope, Bing Crosby and Milton Berle.
   Manheim is survived by his wife, Martha, and his brother, Het.
</TEXT>
