<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Hydroelectric Bjt   07-10 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Hydroelectric, Bjt,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Affecting Hydroelectric Power Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL RAWLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The worst drought since the Dust Bowl of the 1930s is drying up
rivers that normally churn cheap power at hydroelectric dams, and
some higher light bills already are in the mail.
   An Associated Press survey of electric utilities across the
United States turned up no forecasts of major shortages this
summer, but some Western power agencies, dependent on winter's snow
to fill their reservoirs, are worried about continuing drought.
   ``It's over the long term that you start to see impacts _ this
fall and next winter,'' said Steven Schweitzer, deputy area manager
for Western Power Administration at Billings, Mont.
   The American Public Power Association reports that only about
one-eighth of the 2.4 trillion kilowatt hours of electricity
consumed annually in the United States is generated by turbines at
hydroelectric dams. Most utilities can survive without
hydroelectric power _ but may have to pass higher costs of steam
plant generation to their customers.
   The 1 million customers of Alabama Power Co. will find an
increase of 88 cents per 1,000 kilowatt hours in their next bills.
This will push the bill for that amount of energy, considered the
monthly residential average, to $68.11.
   Alabama Power spokesman Chris Conway said the state based its
decision to approve the increase to ``a certain extent'' on the
drought, which has forced the utility to shut down its 14
hydroelectric plants.
   Idaho Power Co. normally produces half its electricity from
hydro plants on the Snake River, now severely low. When more
expensive coal-fired generators began taking up the slack, the
state utilities commission allowed the company to add a $9.6
million annual surcharge to the bills of its 260,000 customers.
   Elsewhere, low rivers could threaten some coal-fired or even
nuclear power plants for want of cooling water, several utility
officials said.
   And while utilities across the nation promise to meet demand,
many said there would be less surplus power to help other utilities
meet peak demands.
   The nation's largest hydroelectric system, Bonneville Power
Administration in the Pacific Northwest, has no immediate problems,
officials said. Streams that feed its 30 federally built reservoirs
depend on runoff from winter snow and are flowing at 70 percent
their normal rate.
   This is far from the driest on record, but Bob Reed, a spokesman
for the agency that serves parts of eight Western states, said
officials are looking at the fall and winter.
   ``Not all the reservoirs will refill this summer and that will
mean next year we will have to operate under more constrained
mode,'' he said.
   The Tennessee Valley Authority, the nation's largest supplier of
electricity, began as a hydroelectric agency but now counts on its
dams for only about 10 percent of the power it furnishes to seven
Southeastern states.
   Stream flow in the Tennessee River and its tributaries is only
20 percent of normal, cutting hydroelectric generation in half and
forcing TVA to spend $117 million extra to produce power.
   ``This additional cost results from replacing low-cost hydro
power with higher cost coal-fired generation and power purchases,''
said Jimmy L. Cross, TVA's vice president for business operations.
In any case, TVA has pledged not to increase rates for the next
three years.
   TVA's hookup with 15 other utilities through 40 tie lines should
make summer shortages the exception rather than the rule, said Hugh
Gardner, manager of TVA's power branch.
   Hayden Timmons, public relations director for Big Rivers
Electric Corp. in western Kentucky, was among those who worried
about a shortage of water and a possible shortage of surplus power.
   Big Rivers does not generate hydroelectric power, but needs
river water for its coal-fired steam plants. At three plants,
Timmons said, the Green and Ohio Rivers are so low that they are
within one to two feet of the water intakes. If the water drops
below the intake lines, the plants would have to close.
   Tal Wright, spokesman for Georgia Power Co. in Atlanta, said the
drought has cut hydroelectric production in half, but nuclear power
plants are producing about half the state's needs, with coal-fired
plants making up the rest.
   Beth Bosch, spokeswoman for the Illinois Commerce Commission,
said that if the drought continues, drying of cooling ponds at the
state's 13 nuclear power plants could be damaging. Commonwealth
Edison operates 12 plants and Illinois Power Co. has one.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
