<DOCNO> AP880710-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-88 1354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a SanctuaryOrBaby-Selling?TrialToRaiseIssues     07-10 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Sanctuary Or Baby-Selling? Trial To Raise Issues</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By SUE MAJOR HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sanctuary supporters say the trial of a
Lutheran minister and a free-lance journalist could focus attention
on the issues surrounding people who flee to the United States from
war-torn Central America.
   But prosecutors contend the case isn't about sanctuary. They say
it's a case of selling babies in an adoption-for-profit scheme.
   The Rev. Glen Remer-Thamert, 44, and Demetria Martinez, 27, were
indicted last Dec. 10, accused of helping two pregnant Salvadoran
women enter the United States illegally in August 1986. Both women
gave birth in the United States, and one of the babies was put up
for adoption.
   The trial begins Wednesday before U.S. District Judge John
Conway.
   Remer-Thamert was indicted on nine counts of conspiracy,
transporting and harboring illegal aliens and mail fraud. Ms.
Martinez was charged with four counts of transporting and inducing
illegal aliens.
   Remer-Thamert's case has been embraced by the sanctuary movement
of clergy and lay people who have been aiding refugees from Central
America since the early 1980s.
   ``For us, it is not something that is against the law, to give
sanctuary to someone fleeing for his or her life,'' said Patricio
Guerrerortiz, a member of the New Mexico Sanctuary Defense
Committee, which was set up to help pay legal expenses.
   Remer-Thamert has said he is being prosecuted because of his
outspoken criticism of the Reagan administration's policies in
Central America.
   Ms. Martinez, a free-lance writer who covers religion for the
Albuquerque Journal and the National Catholic Reporter, has said
she acted solely as a journalist when she accompanied Remer-Thamert
and tried to take steps to ensure she would not even travel with
the women to Albuquerque.
   She also has said she never wrote a story about the women,
partly out of fear for their safety.
   ``I have researched a number of topics that pertain to religion,
including the sanctuary movement and the role of mainline
denominations relative to that movement,'' she said at the time of
her indictment.
   A federal court rule prevents attorneys from discussing the
merits of a case, but legal maneuvering over the past few months
gives some indication of the direction the trial will take.
   U.S. Attorney William Lutz, who will prosecute the case, said in
a court document filed in February that Remer-Thamert was selling
Salvadoran babies for adoption, not helping political refugees.
   ``As soon as the defendant got his hands on the babies, he meant
to transport the women back to El Salvador,'' the document said.
   The indictment accused Remer-Thamert of submitting false expense
documents to Rainbow House International, an adoption agency, and
of receiving $2,900.
   Remer-Thamert said after his indictment that he was reimbursed
for some costs of helping the women but received no fees.
   The women, Cecelia Elias-Alegria and Inez Campos-Anzora, remain
in the United States and are expected to be called as prosecution
witnesses.
   Sanctuary supporters were elated last month when Conway ruled
that a March 28, 1986, proclamation by former Gov. Toney Anaya
declaring New Mexico a sanctuary state could be used by
Remer-Thamert and Ms. Martinez in their defense.
   The proclamation was rescinded by Gov. Garrey Carruthers when he
took office in January 1987.
   Remer-Thamert said last week he was dismissed from his social
services job with the state after the indictment. Since then, he
said, he has been taking care of his two children, writing a book
and raising a garden.
   ``Having been indicted for the first time, I clearly understand
how vulnerable a situation it is to be indicted and how necessary
it is to have supportive friends and family,'' he said.
   A Salvadoran attorney, Luis Arturo Ventura-Rivas, was also named
in the indictment but he will not be on trial because he remains in
El Salvador.
</TEXT>
