<2ND_LINE>AM-Gang Rape,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Begins Monday in Gang Rape Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of 10 men charged in an alleged gang
rape at a cockfight go on trial Monday in this small southern Texas
town which has endured months of questions about the incident.
   A grand jury charged that during a night of gambling, drinking
and drugs, a 19-year-old woman was kidnapped and raped by as many
as 20 men while another dozen men and women either cheered or did
nothing to help her.
   But some residents in the town have said they believe the woman
knew the 10 men she named as her assailants and participated
willingly.
   The two who will stand trial Monday are Orlando Garza and
Corando Perez, both 23; they're charged with aggravated kidnapping
and sexual assault.
   ``I think everybody wants to put it behind them,'' said
Assistant District Attorney Rodolfo Gutierrez, the prosecutor.
   Neither Gutierrez nor the defense asked that the trial be moved
outside this close-knit town of 5,300, about 50 miles west of
Corpus Christi.
   Nine of the 10 defendants are related by blood or by marriage.
Two of the men lived next door to the victim.
   The woman said she was forced into a car with four men after she
declined a ride from them on March 26. She said she was driven
north of town to a tin shed where a cockfight was being held and
where she was repeatedly raped. Cockfights are illegal in the
United States.
   A month after the attack, a special Duval County grand jury
indicted 10 men on 12 counts of kidnapping and sexual assault.
   The woman, her husband, and her two children have since left
town.
   ``They have to get out of town,'' said Richard Yaeger, a family
friend. ``They'll never be able to come back here. These people
here are acting like (the victim and her family) are in the wrong.''
</TEXT>
