<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FakeKidnapping     07-10 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fake Kidnapping,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Two Men In Alleged Fake Kidnappings.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police say they may have solved up to 20 extortion
cases with the arrests of two men who allegedly faked kidnappings
to get money from anxious relatives.
   The two Boston men were arrested Friday and Saturday and are
slated for arraignment Monday on extortion charges.
   They allegedly called a man in suburban Malden and told him they
had kidnapped his nephew and demanded $850 ransom.
   Actually, the nephew had not been abducted, and the hoax was
similar to numerous incidents reported to police.
   ``This has been going on for about a year,'' said Detective Sgt.
William Lang. ``They've been luring people in from the suburbs.
They've never really had anybody.
   ``They just know who these people are, they know their nephew's
names and they know (relatives) won't be able to get hold of them.''
   The break in the case came Friday when the Malden resident,
whose name was not released, told police about the call and ransom
demand.
   The man was told to take the money to a street corner in
Boston's Mattapan section.
   Lang and Malden Police Capt. Raymond Harris took the man's
place, posing as relatives, and made the first arrest.
   ``We're going to be able to clear up a lot of these
extortions,'' said Lang. ``I have 20 reports on my desk right now
of people who have been lured out there.
   ``I hate to think about how many people were too embarrassed to
report anything.''
   Malvin Turner, 26, was arrested Friday; Kenneth Golden, 25, was
taken into custody Saturday.
</TEXT>
