<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CountyAstrologer Bjt   07-10 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-County Astrologer, Bjt,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Astrologer Afraid She Won't Get To Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. CRUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An astrologer has been named to advise one
of Oregon's county commissions, but she says the controversy
surrounding her appointment may prevent her from studying the stars
for Union County.
   Jenny Nicholson was named to the newly created post during the
county commission's regular meeting last week in La Grande, a
farming and timber community of about 12,000 in northeastern Oregon.
   ``What the heck. If the Reagan administration is rumored as
using astrology, I guess we can try it on the local level as
well,'' said county Judge John Howard, a member of the commission
who voted in favor of the appointment.
   Former White House chief of staff Donald Regan disclosed last
month in his book, ``For The Record,'' that Nancy Reagan consulted
an astrologer for aid in helping to prepare President Reagan's
schedule. Mrs. Reagan refused to comment on Regan's assertions.
   In a telephone interview over the weekend from her home in La
Grande, Nicholson said she intended to offer the commissioners
advice on such things as when to apply for government grants and
when best to make presentations.
   ``It was just going to be my community service,'' she said of
the non-paying position.
   But she said the whole idea might be dropped because of
criticism directed by the local newspaper and others at the two
commissioners who voted for her.
   Nicholson, 38, said she moved to La Grande in 1980 from Salem,
where she was a social service worker. The single mother of two
girls, aged 11 and 16, said she supports her family with her
astrology business, ``Otter Space.''
   Nicholson said she had been practicing astrology for 20 years
and that her list of clients from around Oregon and throughout the
West Coast might ``surprise some people.''
   Nicholson said she wanted to do her part to help the county pull
itself out of recent economic doldrums.
   No major governmental decision should be made based on an
astrologer's recommendations, but there is a place for astrology in
government, she said.
   ``There are cycles,'' she said. ``There are heavenly rhythms.''
   In La Grande's case, she said, the time is right to build
bridges with officials in Salem, the state capital.
   ``La Grande is in an extremely high profile ... to get some help
from Salem,'' she said.
   Commissioner Bill Deering, who nominated Nicholson for the job,
said he didn't think it would do any harm to get some astrological
advice, especially since Nicholson is a volunteer.
   ``We need all the help we can with our grants,'' Deering said.
``I respect Jenny greatly and I think her abilities may indeed help
us.''
   Commissioner Marie Lester, however, who abstained from the vote,
said she thought Deering's motion was a joke, adding that she would
have voted against it if she'd known he was serious.
   ``I will not make a decision based on (astrology) nor will I
support the county court making decisions based on that,'' she said.
   In Union County, the county commission is officially known as
the court; the head of the commission is called a judge.
   Lester said she planned a motion at the commission's next
meeting on July 20 to rescind the decision.
   Howard, the judge, said he doesn't take the whole thing
seriously but thinks Nicholson's abilities could be applied to
grant applications.
   ``We may want to talk to her about what day to apply for grants,
just for trial and error to see what happens,'' he said.
</TEXT>
