<HEAD>Twelve Killed In Punjab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen believed to be Sikh militants
killed at least 12 people in the northern state of Punjab,
including four members of a Sikh family, the Press Trust of India
said Sunday.
   The news agency said the attacks occurred Saturday night. It
said three militants entered a home near the town of Hoshiarpur and
opened fire with automatic rifles, killing Gyan Singh, his brother,
Swaran, his son, Devinder, and another family member, Charanjit
Singh.
   The town is 210 miles north of New Delhi.
   The news agency said eight other people, including six Sikhs,
were killed by militants in other parts of the state on Saturday
night.
   No arrests were reported.
   Sikhs form only 2 percent of India's 800 million people but are
a majority in Punjab.
   Radical Sikhs have been fighting for a separate state in Punjab
since 1983, claiming discrimination by India's Hindu majority.
   The latest killings raise to 1,492 the number of people killed
this year in Punjab in Sikh violence.
   Victims of the Sikh separatist insurgency include many moderate
Sikhs, whom the militants accuse of being traitors or police
informers.
