<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-88 1446EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AlohaHearing     07-10 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aloha Hearing,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NTSB To Hold Four-Day Inquiry Into Aloha Jet Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Transportation Safety Board convenes
a four-day hearing this week to try to find out why an 18-foot
chunk ripped away from a Boeing 737 jetliner over Hawaii and what
lessons that accident can teach about the airworthiness of older
aircraft.
   The hearing's main purpose is to help determine the cause of the
April 28 accident, but NTSB officials say the board also wants to
look at how well aging planes are maintained and how corrosion and
fatigue affect their safety.
   The four-day public hearing will open Tuesday.
   A flight attendant was swept to her death and 61 of the 94 other
people aboard Aloha Airlines Flight 243 were injured when a top
portion of the cabin peeled away, as the plane was at 24,000 feet
on a flight from Hilo to Honolulu.
   Although one of the two engines quit, the pilot and co-pilot
managed to control the crippled jet and land it safely on the
island of Maui 13 minutes later. Aviation experts marveled a plane
that badly damaged could land at all.
   The accident spurred a debate within the aircraft industry and
its regulators on the safety of older, heavily used passenger jets.
   The damaged plane, N73711, was built in 1969 and had 89,680
landings. It and two other Aloha 737-200s, both later grounded, had
the highest number of landings, or cycles, of any Boeing Co.
commercial jets, the Seattle-based aircraft manufacturer said.
   Since the acccident, the Federal Aviation Administration has
ordered inspections and repairs of older, high-cycle 737s and in
early June held a three-day conference on aging aircraft.
   Boeing officials have repeatedly said their jets can be flown
almost indefinitely if properly maintained. And Aloha officials
have said they performed all necessary maintenance on their
aircraft.
   But in documents released by the NTSB, Boeing said that seven
months before the accident, it had urged Aloha to make a thorough
structural inspection of N73711 and three other aging 737s.
   Boeing said Aloha, after first agreeing to the inspections in
early 1988, postponed them until the end of this year. Only after a
mid-April meeting with Boeing did the airline agree to reinstate
the inspection program for the four planes, Boeing said.
   In separate documents, Aloha denied it had delayed the
stepped-up inspection and maintenance program.
   Although the inquiry board will examine discrepancies between
the two companies' accounts, the hearing is investigative in nature
and not adversarial, said Boeing spokesman Jack Gamble.
   ``My understanding is that it will be very technical,'' said
Aloha spokesman Milton Goto, adding that the airline will have its
top maintenance and engineering people on hand to testify.
   NTSB spokesman Mike Benson said witnesses from the FAA, Boeing,
Aloha, the Air Transport Association and Britain's Civil Aviation
Authority are expected to testify, along with aerospace experts
from Massachusetts Institute of Technology and the State University
of New York.
   The four-member inquiry board is made up of senior safety board
officials and chaired by NTSB member John K. Lauber, Benson said.
   The NTSB chose Seattle for the hearing because Boeing is based
here and it's roughly equidistant from Hawaii and NTSB headquarters
in Washington, Benson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
