<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Fly-FishingLawmaker 1stLd-Writethru a0725 07-10 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fly-Fishing Lawmaker, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0725,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Senator Takes To The River Bank When Not In Session</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, `From the ...,' to CORRECT spelling to
``Mettawee'' from ``Meadowy.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST PAWLET, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Vermont lawmakers finish their
business late each spring, most members of the part-time, citizen
Legislature have to go back to work as teachers, lawyers and real
estate brokers.
   But not state Sen. David Deen. He's gone fishing.
   From the bustling halls of the Statehouse in Montpelier, Deen
heads for a shin-deep spot along the Big Bend of the Mettawee
River, changing from the tweed jacket of a lawmaker to the vest and
rubber boots of a fly-fishing guide.
   ``I've been busy since the session ended,'' he said on a recent
morning as he watched the cast of Jose Quinones, an
obstetrician-gynecologist from Queens, N.Y., and Deen's student for
the day.
   The Windham County Democrat paused for a moment to reflect on
how he gets to make a living fly-fishing while others toil in
offices and shops or on farms.
   ``I used to chuckle about it,'' he said. ``But hey, this is
work.''
   Deen recently had his first three days off since the legislative
session ended. ``I went fishing all three days,'' he said. ``I have
not tired of the sport just because I do it a lot.''
   Originally from Pennsylvania, Deen came to Westminster in 1971
to help his brother build a house.
   ``We camped out for the entire summer. It rained from June 7th
to July 4th.''
   He landed a job with Southeastern Vermont Community Action, an
anti-poverty agency in Brattleboro, and stayed there 10 years,
moving up to executive director.
   Ronald Reagan was elected president in 1980. It was not a good
year for directors of government-funded community action agencies.
``I started looking around for something to save my sanity,'' Deen
said.
   His brother had given him a fly-fishing rod in 1979, and it
hadn't gotten much use at first. Eventually, though, Deen gave the
sport a try and soon was hooked.
   By 1983, Deen remained at Community Action, but was still
casting about for something else. ``I kept making lists of what I
liked to do and fishing kept coming up. ... So I decided to try
this.''
   Now Deen advertises his service, which he calls ``Strictly
Trout,'' in the Orvis fly-fishing catalogues and other publications
read by enthusiasts in the sport. He gets much of his business
through referrals.
   His day rate is $130 for the first person and $30 for each
additional person.
   It wasn't always so easy. ``For the first three years I was
hungry. I was lucky in that my wife has a good job (with the state
Health Department).'' If either of his two children had decided to
go to college, ``I would have had to get a straight job somewhere.''
   Despite less than perfect conditions, Quinones caught his first
trout early in the day.
   Deen told him a pointer he shares with his students: ``I throw
the fish back. I had a 16-inch rainbow in my hand two nights ago.
It went right back into the Connecticut River. ... I want the fish
to be here.''
</TEXT>
