<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DyingTown     07-10 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dying Town,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dying Town Turns to Tavern in Fight for Survival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW WINDSOR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civic leaders in this financially
depressed town of 850 want to keep their farming community alive _
even if it means legalizing the consumption of liquor 55 years
after the end of Prohibition.
   Village officials want to put the idea to a vote in November;
they call it an economic development issue and a way to keep people
from moving out of town.
   ``Economic conditions are getting worse and worse,'' said Dwayne
Willems, mayor of the town about 60 miles northwest of Peoria.
   ``We're getting more and more empty buildings on Main Street. We
want to promote new business and increase traffic into town
somehow,'' he said.
   ``Right now, there's nothing to come here for,'' said Michael
McCready, owner of Credo's Cafe and a New Windsor village
trustee.``We want somebody who will run a nice tavern where couples
can go, maybe get a sandwich, and keep the rowdy types out.''
   New Windsor isn't much different from a lot of little farming
communities which have gone through hard times in the past decade.
   Many small family farms have disappeared, along with factory
jobs at John Deere, Caterpillar, Farmall, Case and International
Harvester in nearby cities. The jobs often supplemented farmers'
income.
   With its flag-lined Main Street, ``Welcome'' signs and colorful
flower beds in its city park, New Windsor looks in many ways like a
thriving all-American town.
   But there are some all-too-obvious signs of decline. Two banks,
a restaurant, gas station, a coin-operated laundry and grocery
store have all closed their doors.
   Salt and pepper shakers still stand next to napkin holders on
tables in Thurman's Ice Cream Shop, which closed about six weeks
ago.
   The biggest loss was the closing of the school district, which
includes nearby Viola and was annexed by a neighboring district
after running into financial trouble.
   Local leaders are on the verge of launching a petition drive to
get the referendum on the November ballot; they don't expect to
have any trouble rounding up signatures of 25 percent of registered
voters, Willems said Sunday.
   Although residents narrowly rejected a referendum to legalize
liquor consumption in 1974, Willems said that was during good
times, when people just didn't think they needed access to taverns.
   At the grain elevator, the farmers joke that towns like New
Windsor, Alpha and Viola are dry, but the people who live there
aren't. They say many people drive the seven miles to Woodhull or
other towns where beer and liquor flow.
   Not everyone in New Windsor agrees that a tavern in town is a
good idea.
   Bob Sherrard, a longtime insurance agent, said he believes
taverns only bring trouble to small towns.
   ``Let Woodhull keep the trouble,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880710-0046 </DOCNO>
