<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Taiwan-Politics     07-10 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan-Politics,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Proposes Resignation of Older Nationalists</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Taiwan-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Lee Teng-hui proposed Sunday
that half the Central Committee of the governing Nationalist Party
resign to make room for younger members and more native Taiwanese.
   On the fourth day of the 13th party congress, Lee submitted the
names of 180 candidates for the committee, but they did not include
Chiang Wego, the powerful head of the National Security Council and
son of the late Chiang Kai-shek.
   The president's refusal to nominate Chiang Wego seemed designed
to end the rule of the family that for six decades led the
Nationalists and whose most politically influential figure _
President Chiang Ching-kuo, the eldest son of Chiang Kai-shek _
died in January.
   Most of Lee's nominees are expected to be elected Tuesday to the
180-member Central Committee, which makes policy proposals and
assesses party performance. Lee did not nominate at least 10 older
Nationalists from the current 31-member Central Standing Committee.
   The exclusion of the 10 older leaders indicated that Lee, who
was elected party chairman Friday, was seeking to reduce the
influence of conservatives loyal to the Chiang family.
   The leadership of the Nationalist Party, also known as the
Kuomintang, has long been dominated by Old Guard members who fled
to Taiwan with Chiang Kai-shek in 1949, when they lost a civil war
to the Communists on the Chinese mainland.
   The new Central Committee proposed by Lee would have an average
age of 60 _ a drop from the current average of 70. Lee proposed
that only 74 of 150 incumbents remain.
   Nationalist Party Spokesman Raymong Tai said the president wants
to combine new blood with half the old panel so the new committee
``can be forward-looking and can function well.''
   Lee is the first native Taiwanese to lead the Nationalists.
Forty-one percent of his slate is also native Taiwanese, who
comprise 85 percent of the island's nearly 20 million people.
   However, Chinese-born Nationalists hold a majority of seats in
Taiwan's Parliament.
</TEXT>
