<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Ukrainians     07-10 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Ukrainians,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Laments Lack of Freedom for Ukrainian Catholics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Celebrating 1,000 years of Christianity in
what is now the Soviet Union, Pope John Paul II on Sunday embraced
the leader of Ukrainian Catholics and urged freedom of worship for
that underground church.
   Thousands of Ukrainian Catholics from the United States, Canada,
Europe, Australia and South America joined the pope in St. Peter's
Basilica for a nearly three-hour Mass said in the elaborate
Byzantine-Ukrainian rite.
   The Mass was the centerpiece of six days of celebrations in Rome
to mark the advent of Christianity a millennium ago in Kievan Rus,'
the ancient name of what is now the Ukraine, in the western Soviet
Union.
   John Paul recalled how Prince Vladimir converted to
Christianity, leading his people in a mass baptism on the banks of
the Dnieper River in 988.
   ``With all my heart I embrace you as your brother and the first
pope of Slavic origin in the history of the church,'' the
Polish-born pontiff said in Italian in his sermon.
   But, he noted, the Roman Catholic Church's joy at the
celebration ``is tinged with sadness in seeing that so many of your
brothers and sisters do not enjoy religious liberty, despite the
fact that this right has been reaffirmed many times in the
constitutions of the states and in solemn international documents.''
   The pope celebrated Mass with Cardinal Myroslav Ivan
Lubachivsky, who leads the Ukrainian Catholic community worldwide,
including an estimated 4 million followers in the Soviet Union and
about 2 million elsewhere.
   The late Soviet dictator Josef V. Stalin forced the Ukrainian
church in 1946 to officially join the state-sanctioned Russian
Orthodox church. Priests and the unwilling were jailed, deported,
or in some cases, shot.
   Lubachivsky, a Ukrainian-born American citizen, addressed the
pope just before the sermon, speaking in Ukrainian and then in
Italian.
   His voice cracked when he spoke of ``joy clouded over by the
fact that our brothers in the country can not freely profess our
faith and greet the successor of Peter,'' referring to the pope.
   The cardinal, wearing a gold hat studded with precious stones,
then stepped up to the pope, who kissed Lubachivsky on each cheek
and then kissed his hand to the applause of the audience, which
included gold-robed bishops of the Ukrainian church.
   Both the pope and the Ukrainian cardinal expressed hope for
unity with the Russian Orthodox Church.
   The pope recalled that last month he sent a Vatican delegation,
led by the Holy See's No. 2 official, Cardinal Agostino Casaroli,
to Moscow to attend millennium ceremonies of the Russian Orthodox
Church.
   The Ukrainian church broke with the Russian Orthodox in the 16th
century.
   Ukrainians make up about three-fourths of the republic's
population, while Russians constitute about 17 percent.
   The pope has expressed his desire to visit the Soviet Union, but
Vatican officials have said such a pilgrimage could only occur if
the pontiff can travel freely to meet with his flock, including the
Ukrainians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880710-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-88 1607EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-RiverPirate     07-10 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-River Pirate,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`River Pirate' Waits for Aground Boats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT HURON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like the vulture on his cap, Don
Schmidt waits for the unsuspecting _ boaters who run aground in
shallower-than-usual Lake St. Clair.
   ``They cruise through here ... fat, drunk and happy,'' Schmidt
said. ``Then the sand grabs hold of them, and that's all she wrote,
Bucko.
   ``It'll take me an hour to pull them out of there and an hour to
tow them. I'm a real pirate, let me tell you, kid.''
   Schmidt bills a stranded boater $85 an hour for a simple tow,
$150 an hour to pull a boat free after running aground and $330 an
hour for a boat that is so badly stuck that Schmidt has to use his
crane.
   During the past two years, the average depth of the lake between
lakes Huron and Erie has dropped by 2 feet, and this summer's
drought is dropping it even more.
   ``People just got used to the water levels being high,'' said
Lt. Henry Pfeilstucker of the Macomb County sheriff's department
marine division. ``They've got to start looking out, using the
charts and depth-finders again.''
   A depth-finder is one of Schmidt's main tools. He cruises until
his gauge reads 4 feet and waits for someone to run themselves
aground.
   In 1972, a year after Schmidt began Michigan Marine Salvage, one
customer got angry at the price of a tow.
   ``He started swearing and calling me a pirate and a vulture,''
Schmidt remembered. ``And I said, `Vulture, that's it. I've been
looking for a good logo,' and I gave him a job for free.''
</TEXT>
