<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-88 1625EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis     07-10 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Urges Federal Action To Fight Acid Rain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ESTES PARK, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis toured scenic
Rocky Mountain parkland Sunday to highlight his support for
environmental issues and said people should pay higher electric
bills to finance the cleanup of pollution that causes acid rain.
   Dukakis, concluding a hurried Western campaign swing, turned up
the pressure on Republican George Bush over the vice president's
no-tax pledge and brushed aside prospects of potentially
contentious differences with Jesse Jackson going into the
Democratic National Convention next week.
   ``I think Jesse Jackson can do anything he wants to do. I'm
going to the convention and I'm going to win it,'' said Dukakis,
who has enough delegates to assure him the party's presidential
nomination at the convention in Atlanta.
   The Massachusetts governor traveled to Rocky Mountain National
Park northwest of Denver, where he walked around a 9,745-foot
elevation alpine lake, held a news conference and spoke to a small
group of supporters.
   He called for federal action to stop acid rain, a pollution
problem that has damaged lakes and forests of the Northeast and is
increasingly becoming an environmental concern in the West.
   He pointed to a proposal by Northeastern governors to collect
money for cleaning up emissions from electric generating plants,
blamed in part for the problem, by assessing a one-half cent per
kilowatt charge on electric bills.
   He said that amounts to 50-cents a month for the average family
and ``would not be too much to pay for cleaning up this serious
problem.''
   ``The fact of the matter is if we're going to clean up acid rain
in this country, there's going to be a cost,'' he said.
   ``So that's the way we're going to solve the acid rain problem,
and if Mr. Bush doesn't understand that he shouldn't be running for
president of the United States,'' Dukakis said.
   Dukakis hammered anew at Bush's promise not to raise taxes,
repeating his contention that the vice president is supporting what
amounts to higher taxes in the new trade bill and in legislation
extending catastrophic health coverage for the elderly. The health
bill would increase Medicare premiums and add an income tax
surcharge for covered Americans, and the trade bill would assess
certain excise taxes, he said.
   ``I'm for the bill,'' Dukakis said. ``But I want the vice
president to stand up and tell the truth, which is, that he and the
president supported a $6 billion tax increase to pay for needed
health insurance for the elderly in this country.
   ``And when the Congress gives him that new trade bill, they're
going to support another tax increase _ this time an excise on
imported goods to pay for a billion dollars worth of training and
retraining of American workers. I happen to be for that too _ and
so are they. So much for no-tax pledges.''
   He assailed the Reagan administration for failing to spend what
he said was $6 billion that has accumulated in a federal
conservation fund to protect and maintain federal parklands and
valuable wilderness areas.
   Dukakis stood in shirtsleeves and an open collar in an
amphitheater overlooking a valley within the park that has been
reclaimed from development and returned to its natural state. With
him were Gov. Roy Romer and Sen. Timothy Wirth, D-Colo.
   ``I am an ardent conservationist. ... Preserving our environment
is a very conservative policy, and I'm for it,'' Dukakis said.
   The appearance was his last stop on a four-day tour through
Southwest, West Coast and Rocky Mountain regions _ his last
scheduled campaign swing before the convention. He stopped in
states that have gone Republican in recent presidential elections,
including giants California and Texas.
   ``We've made it clear we're not only not going to concede one
single state to the Republicans, we're going to win in the West,''
he said.
   Dukakis was returning to Boston for final deliberations on
selecting a vice presidential candidate and planned a trip to
Washington Tuesday night before meetings the next day with House
Democrats, the Congressional Black Caucus and the national
convention of the NAACP.
   Dukakis said he is ``not frustrated at all'' by Jackson's
refusal to concede him the nomination or posturing on the vice
presidency and convention issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
