<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Protests     07-10 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Protests,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Block Bridge, Demanding Recognition of Opposition
Victory</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mexico Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition party supporters blocked
a bridge linking Mexico to the United States on Sunday and demanded
that the government admit defeat to their party in three
congressional races.
   ``This is to put pressure on the government to let it know the
people will defend their vote,'' said Francisco Barrio, a former
Ciudad Juarez mayor who led more than 1,000 National Action Party
supporters to the Corboba bridge Saturday night.
   Police and the army stayed away from the blocked bridge, where
hundreds of PAN members waved party flags, sat on mattresses and
blankets, listened to music or sang in groups.
   On Saturday night, they set up portable television sets and
watched soccer, and they vowed to remain on the four-lane bridge
until their demands for release of election results and recognition
of PAN victories were met.
   The occupation of the bridge linking Ciudad Juarez with El Paso,
Texas, was one of several coordinated actions of civil disobedience
by PAN backers in northern Chihuahua state.
   Officials of the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party in
Ciudad Juarez said they will challenge the results of any PAN
victories.
   The Pan American highway outside the state capital of Chihuahua,
200 miles south of the U.S. border, was blocked by party members
Saturday night at the same time as the bridge takeover in Ciudad
Juarez.
   Similar traffic stoppages took place in the cities of Delicias,
Jimenez and Parral, all in Chihuahua state.
   ``We are here to defend our vote,'' said Ignacio Montemayor, who
came to the bridge with his wife, Lidia, and 8-year-old daughter
Claudia.
   ``We want to protest against this corrupt government that shames
us before the rest of the world,'' he said.
   The government postponed releasing results from Wednesday's
general elections, and opposition parties claim massive vote
rigging by the government and the governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party, PRI.
   Under the election code, district committees should have results
Sunday, but it wasn't clear when the Federal Election Commission
would give the complete results of the vote.
   PRI has claimed victory for its presidential candidate, Carlos
Salinas de Gortari. Leftist opposition leader Cuauhtemoc Cardenas
also claimed victory. The third major candidate, Manuel J.
Clouthier of PAN, said Saturday that a count carried out by his
supporters showed him ahead.
   PAN officials showed copies of polling booth certificates signed
by all parties to back up its claim to victory in three districts.
</TEXT>
