<DOCNO> AP880710-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-88 1703EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BuddhistTemple     07-10 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Buddhist Temple,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Largest North American Buddhist Temple Near Completion in LA
Suburb</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LUIS TORRES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HACIENDA HEIGHTS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buddhist leaders have overcome
neighborhood resistance toward building the largest Buddhist temple
in North America and are racing to finish the 15-acre complex in
time for the religion's international conference this November.
   The complex will be known as the Hsi Lai Buddhist Temple, ``the
temple that came to the West from the East,'' said Rev. Shih Yung
Kai, abbess of the temple.
   It sits on a hill 20 miles east of Los Angeles in this
upper-middle-class neighborhood, one of many suburbs swollen by a
huge influx of Asians in recent years.
   The Taiwan-based Fo Kuang Shan Buddhist society is building the
temple and will be host of the 16th International Buddhist General
Conference there in November, the first time this gathering will be
held in the West. The conference, entitled ``Unity for World
Peace,'' is expected to attract 300 participants from 40 countries,
Ms. Yung Kai said.
   When plans for the $14 million temple and monastery were
announced six years ago, some neighbors feared it would disrupt
this quiet residential area.
   ``Many people in the community don't know much about Buddhism,
and that can bring suspicion,'' she said. ``Above all we want
people to know we're not a cult, something strange. I think people
here now understand that.''
   Buddhism was founded in India about 500 B.C. by Buddha. The
religion's roughly 250 million followers, mainly in Asia, believe
that correct thinking and self-denial will enable their souls to
reach nirvana, a state of ultimate enlightenment. There are fewer
than a million Buddhists in North America.
   The Rev. Paul Louie, a now-retired Presbyterian minister,
organized several public meetings between local residents and
temple representatives.
   ``There was suspicion about the temple but also resistance due
to the fact that lots of Asians were moving into that
neighborhood,'' he said.
   ``Some residents thought it would be some kind of religious
cult, some kind of Hare Krishna thing with people chanting and
parading through the streets with tambourines. Of course, it's
nothing like that.''
   Barbara Lee Fish of the Hacienda Heights Improvement Association
said those fears are ``a thing of the past.''
   ``We're a community that's pulling together,'' she said. ``I
think the great majority of residents here will welcome the temple
when they open their doors.''
   Fears that home prices would plunge also have abated, according
to real estate agent Wayne Grey. ``Property values have actually
skyrocketed in the area,'' he said.
   Construction and legal problems arose in trying to build a
Chinese-style complex while accommodating Los Angeles County
building codes, Western construction methods and ``American ways of
doing things,'' according to architect Anthony Yang.
   Still, ``there's no doubt in my mind that we'll finish the work
by the (Nov. 1) deadline,'' said Steve Frank, spokesman for
Technical Management Services, the building contractor.
   The 10-building complex is a scaled-down replica of the mammoth,
ornate Fo Kuang Shan temple in Taipei, and will include a main
shrine, a monastery for 50 monks and nuns, a library and meeting
rooms.
   At the site last week, workers were installing more than 1,000
Buddha statues, each about a foot tall, on the walls of the main
shrine, a cavernous hall that will hold 800 worshipers. The
shrine's centerpiece, a two-ton golden chandelier made of dangling
gold-plated bells, will hang 50 feet above the marble floor, Ms.
Yung Kai said.
   Presbyterian minister Larry Boles, whose church is in the long
shadow cast by the hillside temple, said residents have been
awe-struck by the construction over the last three years.
   ``In the beginning it was just a bit of activity on the hill,''
he said. ``It went from a few little wooden structures to what it
is now _ something that looks like a giant, glittering palace.''
</TEXT>
