<DOCNO> AP880710-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-88 1721EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Economy     07-10 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Economy,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central Committee To Discuss Economic Reform Alternatives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The communist party daily in an
unprecedented report has detailed two variations for long-term
economic development and reform to be discussed by the party
leadership at a meeting this week.
   Hungary's Premier and party leader, Karoly Grosz, has been
quoted as saying the Central Committee meeting which begins
Wednesday is to be broadcast live on television and radio, also an
first-time event.
   The report Saturday in the party daily Nepszabadsag marked the
first time a detailed agenda for a Central Committee meeting was
published in advance. It outlined a what it called a radical
market-oriented reform proposal and a more moderate path that would
introduce reform gradually.
   In a separate article in Nepszabadsag, Rezso Nyers, considered
the father of Hungary's 1968 economic reforms, warned the
``disorder'' which accompanies reform should not lead to a
rejection of change.
   ``Crisis is ... social acknowledgement that things have to be
done in a different way,'' said Nyers, recently reappointed to the
ruling Politburo after having been ousted from that body in 1975.
   ``At the beginning any reform looks like disorder versus an
orderly state,'' Nyers told the daily. ``If this disorder goes
beyond a certain limit, even masses of people might call for
order.''
   Nyers said ``the great test of reform policy'' was keeping the
``disorder'' limited.
   Nepszabadsag, in its report on the two economic proposals to be
discussed by the Central Committee, said the first variation up for
discussion would focus on ``radical restructuring'' towards a more
market oriented economy that could, however, lead to 80,000 to
100,000 unemployed and result in greater social tensions in the
wake of reduced living standards.
   The second variation ``could be seen as a more consistent
continuation of the practice followed until now,'' introducing
reforms more gradually, the paper said.
   Unemployment would remain within the limits of 30,000 to 50,000.
Unemployment was expected to reach about 50,000 already this year.
   The paper said that although the second option would mean less
social tensions in the short-term, the danger of falling behind
international norms ``would not disappear.''
   Nyers in his interview said he had always been an advocate of
``reform-minded communism,'' saying the country must reject the
1950s. ``My stand is politically and ideologically breaking away
without any acquittal,'' Nyers was quoted as saying.
   If the Hungarian and other Communist parties do not do so,
``they would be unable to change the situation as it ought to be
changed,'' Nyers said.
   Popular revulsion against the repressive communist regime of
Matyas Rakosi, a protege of Soviet dictator Josef V. Stalin,
sparked the 1956 uprising in Hungary which was quelled by Soviet
forces.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
