<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-10 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Keep Parts Northwestern Texas Soaked</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms dumped locally heavy rain on parts of Texas on
Sunday, and thunderstorms also were scattered over the parched
Midwest and the South.
   Temperatures hit 100 along the East Coast.
   Slow-moving storms dumped rain on parts of northwestern Texas,
where the ground was saturated from heavy rainfall the previous
several days, and some streets and highways were flooded, the
National Weather Service said.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered from the Great
Lakes region through the middle Mississippi Valley along a cold
front that was slowly pushing eastward, bringing relief from the
latest heat wave over the Ohio Valley.
   Severe thunderstorm watches were issued for parts of Michigan,
Indiana and Ohio.
   Much of Iowa had picked up at least a half-inch of rainfall
since Saturday morning, not enough to dent the drought. Parts of
southwestern Iowa measured up to 2 inches of rain, parts of central
Iowa got up to 3 inches and Lansing, in the northeastern corner,
picked up 3.85 inches.
   Showers and thunderstorms also clustered across much of the
lower Mississippi Valley and the central Gulf Coast region, and
showers and thunderstorms also were scattered in northwestern and
central Florida.
   Showers and thunderstorms were accompanied by high wind and
small hail from western parts of Virginia into western North
Carolina. The storms also were scattered from northern Maine
southwestward into northern parts of New Hampshire and Vermont.
   Elsewhere, thunderstorms developed along the eastern foothills
of the Colorado Rockies, and in central and eastern Wyoming.
   High temperatures soared above 90 degrees across parts of the
East Coast, reaching 98 at New York City and 100 at Washington.
Baltimore's airport hit a record 100 and Roanoke, Va., reached a
record 96. The record of 95 was tied at Buffalo, N.Y., giving the
city its seventh consecutive day of records.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Crescent City, Calif., to 107 at Las Vegas, Nev. The
early-morning low for the day was 37 at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Monday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the upper and middle Rio Grande Valley of Texas through the
southern Plains, Arkansas and the lower Mississippi Valley, the
lower Ohio and Tennessee valleys, the Gulf Coast, Florida and much
of the Atlantic Coast region into New England. Thunderstorms
developing in the afternoon were forecast along the high Plains of
South Dakota, Wyoming and Nebraska.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted along the Pacific Coast into
western and central Washington state, and in much of the northern
Plains; between 100 and 110 degrees across the desert Southwest;
and in the 80s or 90s across most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
