<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0772 07-10 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0772,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Urges Bush to `Tell The Truth' on Fees Increase</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS lead to UPDATE; INSERTS grafs 11-12 with Bush comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis on Sunday urged rival George Bush to ``tell the
truth'' about whether his support for an increase in fees for
health coverage indicates the vice president favors an increase in
taxes. Bush, meanwhile, called for caution in dealing with the
Soviets.
   The vice president spent the weekend at his seaside retreat in
Kennebunkport, Maine, and sought the support of Lithuanians at a
local festival.
   Bush said last week that he favors higher fees for some
government services, including higher payments for Medicare
recipients under the catastrophic health care coverage of recent
legislation. Dukakis said Bush's plan amounts to raising taxes.
   ``I'm for the bill,'' Dukakis said as he campaigned in the
Denver area. ``But I want the vice president to stand up and tell
the truth, which is, that he and the president supported a $6
billion tax increase to pay for needed health insurance for the
elderly in this country.''
   The all-but-certain Democratic nominee turned aside questions
about a possible clash with opponent Jesse Jackson at the national
convention in Atlanta next week.
   ``I think Jesse Jackson can do anything he wants to do,''
Dukakis said. ``I'm going to the convention and I'm going to win
it.''
   Jackson denied reports on Saturday that he and his delegates
might stage a walkout at the convention. ``The threat is not that
we're going to walk out. The threat is that we're going to stay and
expand and build and grow and make a difference,'' Jackson said.
   He gave no indication of surrendering to Dukakis, who has
amassed the number of delegates needed to win the nomination on the
first ballot.
   ``My name will be in nomination,'' Jackson said. ``We will have
(platform) planks on the floor, those that are not resolved between
now and that time, and that should be a reasonable expectation.''
   Bush, putting politics on hold for the summer weekend, delivered
a non-partisan speech to a Lithuanian festival held at a
40-year-old Franciscan monastery.
   Citing reforms in the Soviet Union under Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev, the vice president said, ``This is a time of change in
the Soviet Union, and for the Lithuanian people, it is a time for
hope.''
   But, he added, ``If this is a time for hope, it is not a time
for complacency or weakness. It is a time, I believe, to test
whether the reforms are genuine.''
   The likely Republican nominee also spent time on his boat and
attended Sunday church services with his family.
   Dukakis used a tour of the Rocky Mountains at Estes Park, Colo.,
to focus attention on environmental problems, including acid rain,
which kills trees and fish. Its effects have been felt mainly in
Canada and the Northeast.
   The Massachusetts governor suggested an increase in utility
payments for residential electricity customers amounting to 50
cents per family per month to help solve the problem.
   ``The fact of the matter is if we're going clean up acid rain in
this country there's going to be a cost,'' Dukakis said. ``That's
why we're going to solve the acid rain problem, and if Mr. Bush
doesn't understand that he shouldn't be running for president.''
   Dukakis planned to return to Boston to concentrate on the vice
presidential selection process, which entered the final stretch
with the convention just over a week away.
   ``I love picking people, I enjoy this process, it's an important
choice and I'm going to make it,'' Dukakis said when asked by
reporters about a possible running mate. ``I'm going to make it
with all the information, advice and counsel I can. I can't tell
you when that's going to be.''
</TEXT>
