<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Lithuania     07-10 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Lithuania,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lithuanians Rally To Discuss Conference Results</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lithuania's delegates to a national Communist
Party conference told 100,000 people at a rally in the western
Soviet republic that their demands for more autonomy received a
warm response in the Kremlin, Tass said.
   The official Soviet news agency said the rally Saturday, led by
a group called the ``Lithuanian Movement for Perestroika,'' was
attented by residents of the republic's capital, Vilnius, and
Lithuanian delegates to last week's national party conference in
Moscow.
   ``Perestroika'' is the Russian word for Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's economic, cultural and political reform program.
   Tass quoted the delegates as telling the rally Lithuanians'
proposals for ``development of independence'' and expansion of
rights of the 15 Soviet republics, wider use of their national
languages and measures to preserve the environment were adopted at
the four-day Kremlin session that ended July 1.
   Members of the movement _ writers, scientists and cultural
figures _ spoke in favor of perestroika. The speakers condemned
stagnation and bureaucracy and declared their group rejects
``nationalist and extremist elements,'' Tass said.
   Similar groups have been formed in the two other Soviet
republics on the Baltic Sea _ Latvia and Estonia. The groups want
to assume financial control over industries in the republics from
ministries in Moscow, and also control over environmental and
cultural policies affecting their republics.
   At a rally in Vilnius on June 24, demonstrators carried
Lithuania's national flag, according to the Lithuanian Information
Center in New York, an emigre group. In earlier times, carrying the
flag used during Lithuania's brief independence between the world
wars would have prompted arrests. Now it is apparently tolerated by
local authorities.
   Many residents of the three Baltic republics resent the Soviet
takeover of their areas in 1940, conducted under a secret section
of a pact between Nazi Germany and the Kremlin the year before. The
United States and several other Western countries do not recognize
the Soviet takeover and consider the Baltic republics independent.
   In a separate report, Tass said a rally to commemorate the Jews
of Vilnius was held Friday. People gathered on the site of the
former Jewish ghetto in the capital to ask authorities to come up
with a way of ``perpetuating the memory of the people perished''
when Nazi forces swept through the area in 1941, massacring
thousands of Jews, virtually the entire Jewish population of the
area.
</TEXT>
