<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru   07-10 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0713,0705</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tass Says Guerrilla Attacks Kill or Wound 150; Commander Warns
Pakistan on Rebel Aid</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 5th graf, The rebels... with 1 graf to CLARIFY Tass said
150 killed or wounded. Pick up 6th pvs, ``In retaliation...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan rebels bombarded cities and towns across
Afghanistan with rockets and artillery fire in a wave of attacks
that killed or wounded more than 150 civilians, Tass reported
Sunday.
   Tass said in a report from Kabul, the Afghan capital, that the
raids occurred over the past 48 hours. It said caravans carrying
weapons for the rebels were arriving from Pakistan.
   The Soviet military commander in Afghanistan said the Kremlin
might be forced to rethink its schedule for the withdrawal of
troops if Pakistan keeps sending aid to Afghan guerrillas, a
newspaper reported.
   Two caravans of 350 pack animals recently brought a ``large
amount'' of arms and ammunition to the outskirts of the town of
Talukana, the official Soviet news agency reported.
   The rebels used artillery and rockets to shell populated areas
in more than eight provinces, including the capital district of
Kabul, and more than 150 civilians were killed or wounded, Tass
said. In Samagan province alone, it said, 29 people, including 16
children, were killed in attacks on villages.
   ``In retaliation, the Afghan armed forces in a number of
provinces smashed extremist groups,'' Tass said, adding that
``several tens'' were killed. It said more than 20 insurgents died
when armed detachments from rival rebel groups battled among
themselves.
   Lt. Gen. Boris Gromov, the top Soviet soldier in Afghanistan,
stopped short of saying the Soviets might slow down or stop the
pullout of troops.
   Answering questions from the Krasnaya Zvezda military daily,
Gromov said all Soviet troops have now been withdrawn from the
eastern and southeastern provinces of Afghanistan.
   In April, the Soviets signed accords in Geneva that committed
them to begin withdrawing their more than 100,000 soldiers from
Afghanistan on May 15 and to complete the pullout within 10 months.
They intervened in Afghanistan in 1979 to back the government in
its war against anti-Marxist guerrillas.
   ``We are prepared to continue to implement strictly and
faithfully the provisions of the Geneva agreements,'' Gromov was
quoted as saying. ``Although I do not rule out that unceasing
violations of the provisions by Pakistan may lead, as was pointed
out in the recent statement of the U.S.S.R. Ministry of Foreign
Affairs, to a situation when appropriate conclusions will be made
as regards the timetable of the troop withdrawal.''
   He did not elaborate.
   The Foreign Ministry on May 28 said if Pakistan did not halt
``interference in the internal affairs of Afghanistan,'' the Soviet
Union ``would draw pertinent conclusions with respect to the
timetable of the troop withdrawal and take concrete steps.''
   The Soviet Union has repeatedly complained that Pakistan is
violating the Geneva accord by sending arms to guerrillas fighting
the Kabul government and by allowing guerrilla training bases in
its territory.
   Gromov told the newspaper, ``As our troops are withdrawn from
provinces that border on Pakistan, the desire of the opposition to
give broader scope to fratricidal war becomes increasingly
noticeable. There are numerous facts which confirm that the
Pakistani side does not intend to observe the spirit and the letter
of the Geneva agreements.''
   The Communist Party daily Pravda also accused Pakistan on Sunday
of breaching the accords. Apparently referring to American arms
shipments to the Afghan guerrillas, Pravda said ``U.S. actions''
also ran counter to the spirit of the agreements.
   ``It is clear that the one who violates them assumes grave
responsibility for the consequences and for the disappointment of
the Afghans' hopes for a peaceful life,'' the paper said.
   The United States has been supplying the Afghan rebels with arms
and supplies channeled through Pakistan. It has vowed to continue
the supplies as long as the Soviet Union keeps up its military
support of the Afghan government.
   The Geneva accords prohibit Pakistani interference in
Afghanistan's affairs. But weapons supply from the Soviet Union is
not banned. A separate agreement signed by Moscow and Washington
allows the superpowers to continue supplying their respective
allies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
