<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Claims To Recapture More Of Its Northeastern Mountains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said its forces on Sunday recaptured
more of its strategic border peaks from Iranian troops in a second
day of battles in the mountainous northeastern region, a military
communique reported.
   The communique broadcast by state-run radio said a dozen heights
in Kurdistan and a border post near the town of Penjwin, seized by
Iran four years ago, have been retaken.
   There was no immediate Iranian comment to the latest Iraqi
claims. These followed Saturday's Iraqi claim that 14 peaks were
liberated in the Penjwin area after a four-day battle.
   Iranian military communiques, carried by the official Islamic
Republic News Agency in dispatches monitored in Cyprus, said only
that Iranian jets carried out 13 sorties against Iraqi troop
concentrations in various sectors of the extensive front line,
inflicting heavy losses.
   The agency said Iraqi forces shelled the southern city of
Khoramshahr, inflicting damage but no reported casualties, but the
Iraqi military spokesman denied the city was shelled.
   IRNA added that a number of civilians were killed following an
Iraqi artillery bombardment since Saturday afternoon of the town of
Sardasht, 50 miles northeast of Penjwin.
   It also said a civilian was killed and 150 were injured in an
Iraqi chemical-weapon raid in western Iran. Iraq denied carrying
out such a raid.
   The Iraqi News Agency said a military spokesman denied that
Sardasht had been shelled.
   ``These allegations are compltely baseless and untrue and they
are aired by the Iranian regime to cover up its successive defeats
at the hands of the Iraqi armed forces,'' INA quoted the spokesman
as saying.
   The Iraqi action to drive the Iranians out of the mountains of
Iraqi Kurdistan follows important Iraqi military victories in other
sectors of the front earlier this year in the countries' nearly
8-year-old war.
   The Iraqis retook Faw, an oil port at the southern end of the
battlefront, in April. They followed this up with the liberation of
the Shalamcheh region and the southern oil-rich Majnoon islands
last month.
   INA also reported that Iraq formally complained Sunday ``of the
new Iranian crime of killing prisoners of war.''
   The agency said Arab ambassadors accredited to Baghdad were
summoned to the Foreign Ministry and were given messages explaining
``the new Iranian crime.''
   INA did not give additional details beyond saying that an
unspecified number of Iraqi prisoners of war ``were brutally killed
after being tied with ropes.''
   It said the bodies were found when Iraqi troops retook the
Iranian-occupied town of Mawat, in Iraqi Kurdistan, on May 15.
   In the Persian Gulf, two Iranian gunboats intercepted four
Kuwaiti fishing boats inside Kuwait's territorial waters but
released the occupants along with one boat, the Kuwait News Agency
reported Sunday.
   The agency, quoting an Interior Ministry official, said the
incident occurred Friday.
   Several Iranian islands lie close to Kuwaiti waters, including
Farsi which is a stronghold of Iranian armed speedboats that carry
out attacks on neutral shipping in the waterway in retaliation for
Iraqi strikes on Iranian oil routes.
   Despite repeated warnings from the Kuwaiti authorities,
fishermen often go close to the Iranian territorial waters in quest
of good catches.
</TEXT>
