<HEAD>Bush Warns Against `Complacency' In Dealing With Soviets</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS graf 16 pvs, Bush was, to CORRECT day of NAACP speech</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said
Sunday that recent changes within the Soviet Union may herald ``a
time of hope'' for those living in eastern Europe but cautioned
against ``complacency or weakness'' in dealing with the Soviets.
   Addressing a Lithuanian festival, Bush challenged the Soviet
Union to make good on its reforms toward openness by relaxing its
grip on the nations it occupied after World War II.
   ``The United States has always condemned the violation of your
national sovereignity, and in the years ahead we will never condone
the forced occupation of Lithuania by the Soviet Union,'' he said.
   Bush spoke at a Lithuanian Franciscan monastery in this small
seacoast resort town where he has a vacation home.
   It was his only public appearance during a weekend of rest. And
his brief remarks were largely nonpartisan.
   The certain Republican presidential nominee said that despite
the recent thaw in U.S-Soviet relations, full compliance by the
Soviets with international agreements on human rights remains ``an
essential element in improving relations between our two
countries.''
   Still, Bush told the gathering on the monastery grounds, ``this
is a time of change in the Soviet Union, and for the Lithuanian
people, it is a time for hope.''
   ``There is hope because talk of nationalism is no longer merely
whispered behind closed doors. We see it shouted in the streets
during the demonstrations that grow larger by the day.''
   Bush cited the pullout of Soviet troops from Afghanistan as
further cause for hope of a change in Soviet policy.
   But, he added, ``If this is a time for hope, it is not a time
for complacency or weakness. It is a time, I believe, to test
whether the reforms are genuine.''
   The monastery where Bush spoke was founded by Franciscan fathers
who emigrated to southern Maine in 1947 when their country fell to
invading Soviets.
   After speaking, Bush and his wife Barbara watched a performance
by a Lithuanian-American dance troupe from Boston.
   Earlier, Bush attended a church service with his wife and his
87-year-old mother, Dorothy Walker Bush, at an Episopalian church
near his summer home.
   Otherwise, his weekend was taken up by fishing, boating and
family events, said spokeswoman Shelia Tate.
   ``He really came up here to relax,'' she said.
   Bush was to speak to an agricultural group on Monday and to
address an NAACP meeting in Washington on Tuesday. He also plans to
attend the All-Star baseball game in Cincinnati on Tuesday.
   Bush plans to do some campaigning during next week's Democratic
National Convention, although details of his schedule have not yet
been set, said Ms. Tate.
   In his speech at the monastery, Bush told a group of about
1,000, ``it is 48 years now since the Soviet Union invaded your
homeland and the other Baltic states. Tragically, many of you were
forced to flee Soviet persecution; your children may never know the
thrill of laughing and playing on Lithuanian soil.''
   He called for the release of Lithuanian political prisoners,
restoration of the right of Lithuanian Catholics to worship freely,
and ``restoring the birthright of freedom to the Lithuanian
people.''
   ``All of us look upon freedom as a gift, a gift from God,'' Bush
said. ``Accepting the suppression of the most fundamental human
freedoms would be turning our backs on our own values and
heritage.''
   ``Only the United States is strong enough and committed enough
to stand up for the freedoms of oppressed people all over the
world,'' he said.
</TEXT>
