<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DietPatch-Reagan     07-10 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Diet Patch-Reagan,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mike Reagan Appears in Ads for Diet Patch Banned by FDA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Reagan, the older son of President
Reagan, said he wants a commercial in which he endorses a diet aid
to be pulled from television if federal officials determine the
patches are being marketed illegally.
   Reagan appears in a 30-minute talk-show style commercial for an
appetite-control skin patch that the Food and Drug Administration
is investigating. He said he appeared in the commercial ``as an
actor.''
   The commercial, with Reagan acting as a talk show host, began
appearing on Los Angeles cable channel KSCI on June 7 and is
scheduled to run through the end of July.
   The FDA banned distribution of all such diet patches in mid-May
because they are classified as drugs and require FDA approval for
sale to the public, said FDA compliance officer Greg Nelson. The
agency only found out about the brand of patches Reagan advertised
within the past two weeks, he said.
   Reagan, the 43-year-old adopted son of the president and his
first wife, actress Jane Wyman, told the Los Angeles Daily News he
wants the advertisement to be taken off the air if the FDA
determines that the patches are being marketed illegally. He said
he was unaware that the FDA had banned the patches already.
   ``I don't want my name out there,'' he was quoted as saying.
   Reagan wears one of the patches during the show, which features
testimonials of doctors and satisfied users, but he said he does
not use the patches.
   ``I auditioned as an actor and was hired to do the job,'' Reagan
was quoted as saying. ``It could have been baby bottles. I knew it
(the product) from nothing.''
   The product, called Eurotrym Diet Patches, is marketed by AmEuro
Services International Inc.
   Dr. Keith Kenyon, a San Fernando Valley doctor who said he
invented the patches about a year ago, confirmed the FDA
investigation.
   ``They wanted to know what was going on, because there was never
an application (for licensing) filed,'' he said.
   Officials with AmEuro, which markets the patches out of Phoenix,
Ariz., could not be reached for comment. There was no telephone
listing for the company in Phoenix.
   The patches contain a mix of natural substances, Kenyon said.
They are applied to an acupuncture point and stimulate the body, he
claimed.
   Similar diet patches marketed under the name Appetoff by
Meditrend International, a San Diego company, were seized in May by
the FDA.
   Nelson said it was unlikely Reagan would be a target of an
investigation unless he was involved in distribution or sales of
the alleged diet aid.
   In 1980 and 1981, Reagan was investigated for several business
dealings and was served with two search warrants, but the
investigation was later dropped. In 1981, he resigned from his job
after he used his father's name in a letter soliciting contracts
for his employer from military bases.

</TEXT>
