<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Holocaust     07-10 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Holocaust,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Holocaust Conference in Oxford</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of scholars and writers from
around the world gathered in this university city Sunday as the
International Holocaust Conference on the impact of Nazi genocide
on the modern world.
   In an opening speech, Czechoslovak-born newspaper publisher
Robert Maxwell appealed to Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev to
``disclose the truth'' about Raoul Wallenberg, the Swedish diplomat
who disappeared in Hungary while helping save thousands of Jews
from Nazi gas chanbers in 1944.
   Wallenberg was reported to have been seen in Soviet prison camps
12 years after the Soviets say he died in Moscow's Lubyanka prison
in 1947.
   ``It is only by remembering the past that we can guard against
its repetition in the future,'' said Maxwell, who is chairman of
the weeklong conference that has drawn more than 500 scholars and
writers from 48 countries.
   Maxwell broke down at the end of his speech and sobbed as he
said of the Holocaust: ``We must not let this happen again.''
   Most of Maxwell's family were were among the 6 million Jews who
died in the Holocaust. His wife, Dr. Elisabeth Maxwell, organized
the conference and on Sunday called upon people of all faiths to
join together to stamp out anti-Semitism. She is a Christian.
   During the closed session at Oxford and a public session in
London this Friday, the conference _ the first of its kind in
Britain _ will consider the impact of the Holocaust on the
contemporary world and the role of Christianity ``in creating a
climate of opinion that made it possible,'' the organizers said.
   Other events include a season of films in London and exhibitions
of some of the art produced by concentration camp victims.
</TEXT>
