<2ND_LINE>AM-Roof Collapse, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0765,0770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crowd Applauds `Miracle Child' As Brownsville Memorial Held</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with memorial service, CORRECT
that at least 47 injured, sted 47. Picks up 8th graf pvs, `Poos
said...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XBRO1, XBRO2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two thousand people gathered at the
site of what had been a three-story department store Sunday night
to pay tribute to the victims, the survivors and the rescuers in
last week's building collapse.
   Workers cleared away the remaining rubble from the site Sunday,
the day after the last of the 14 bodies were recovered from the
debris left when the Amigo store fell down during a torrential
rainstorm Thursday.
   The crowd gave a standing ovation to Denise Carrera, the
8-year-old ``miracle child'' who was found virtually unscathed
under the debris Friday. The child, dressed in a blue dress,
clutched a candle as she came to the stage as a tribute to the
community's accomplishment.
   Brownsville Mayor Ygnacio Garza said the emergency was over and
thanked the hundreds of volunteers and authorities who assisted in
three days of rescue efforts.
   ``I think this community did and proved what all of us already
knew _ that we are a great city with great friends,'' Garza told
the audience. ``It now is time to bring this chapter to an end.''
   Many of the volunteers and local officials hugged each other and
the families of the victims as the ceremony came to an end.
   In all, at least 47 people were injured in the disaster, which
officials said may have been cause by the buildup of water on the
store's roof. Little Denise was one of six survivors pulled from
the rubble Friday. Her mother and 4-year-old brother were among
those killed.
   Garza, who coordinated the rescue effort, said investigations
into the collapse will begin this week. Another building might
never be built on the store site, he said.
   ``It's been suggested that a memorial plaza be erected on this
site,'' Garza said. ``I think this would be an excellent site for a
plaza. The idea strikes me very well, but with only six hours sleep
in the past three days, a lot of ideas strike me well.''
   Crews worked throughout the night Saturday, using heavy
machinery to remove remaining concrete and steel after they
determined no more survivors or bodies were in the rubble.
   Police Sgt. Dean Poos said the memorial service was intended to
thank the rescuers and other volunteers.
   ``A lot of the people will be going back to work Monday at 8
o'clock and this is just our way of saying `This is over,''' he
said.
   
   Poos said most of the cordoned-off streets near the site would
be opened early Monday, except for those within a block of the
collapsed building.
   Garza said he would speak with officials from the Federal
Emergency Management Agency to discuss emergency aid.
   He said concrete and steel trusses and other parts of the
building have been taken to insurance investigators, steel
manufacturers and city officials for analysis to determine the
cause of the accident.
   Officials believe a large pool of water collected on top of the
roof after more than 2 inches of rain fell in the area Thursday
afternoon.
   But Garza said there were numerous theories on the collapse,
including that roof drains were not clear. He said he would wait
for the investigation before placing blame.
   ``The insurance adjusters have taken some photographs, but their
job will be more difficult because everything has been
dismantled,'' Garza said.
   Officials had originally said 16 people died in the collapse,
but near the end of the search Saturday they found only one body in
an area where they had expected to find three.
   Residents across the Rio Grande Valley gathered in churches to
pray for the victims and families.
   ``People came from all over the Valley, from all over the state
to give their assistance and time,'' the Rev. Warren Brown told
about 500 worshippers at Immaculate Conception Cathedral, three
blocks from the accident site.
   ``There were people who may have never seen one another who came
to work together to save lives and comfort the bereaved,'' Brown
said.
   The mayor said he was thankful to hundreds of local volunteers
and especialy grateful to experts from across the country who
helped in the rescue effort.
   Most out-of-state experts, including seismic workers and
underground rescue teams, began heading home Sunday.
</TEXT>
