<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Rig, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0773,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Mourns Disaster Victims; Workers Battle Rig Fire And High
Winds</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4 ``The disaster...the platform'' with two grafs
to UPDATE with some survivors still hospitalized; fire still
burning early Monday. Pickup 5th graf pvs ``Conti urged...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LON 4,5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents at Sunday church services
mourned family and friends killed in an oil rig disaster in the
North Sea and saluted the thousands of men working on other
offshore rigs.
   Roman Catholic Bishop Mario Conti read a message from Pope John
Paul II, who said he learned of Wednesday's explosion and fire
``with deep sorrow.''
   The disaster at the Piper Alpha rig 120 miles off Scotland's
east coast killed 166 workers. Fourteen of the 64 survivors were
still being treated in Aberdeen Royal Infirmary, three of them with
extensive burns.
   At the rig, Texas oil troubleshooter ``Red'' Adair and his crew
battled high winds Sunday in a fight to put out the blaze on what
remains of the platform. The fire was still burning early Monday.
   Conti urged 600 worshipers, included many black-clad mourners,
at a Requiem Mass to ensure that high safety standards are
maintained by oil companies ``and even bettered, and that no
unessential risks are taken, whatever the cost.''
   Tom O'Neill, 56, safety manager with the Odeco exploration firm
that discovered the Piper Oil field, spoke on behalf of oilmen to
those gathered in St. Mary's Cathedral.
   ``I ask you as an oilman to pray not only for the deceased and
the next-of-kin, but for all the living, and those who are out
there,'' he said.
   Conti said the enormity of the Piper Alpha disaster sent ``shock
waves well beyond our shores.''
   ``His Holiness (the pope) invokes eternal rest upon the
deceased, and God's comforting blessings upon the survivors and all
affected by the tragedy,'' Conti said, reading the pontiff's
message.
   But the bishop said the full impact of the world's worst
oilfield disaster was felt in Aberdeen and other parts of northeast
Scotland, where 40 percent of the victims lived.
   ``We have been, and are, proud of their achievements,'' he said.
``We mourn now their tragic deaths ... along with members of the
rescue parties.''
   ``They have worked for our benefit ... adding immeasurably to
the quality of our lives,'' he said.
   A memorial service for the victims is to be held July 20.
   The 73-year-old Adair was directing his firefighting team from
the support-vessel Tharos, alongside the disaster rig, said a
spokesman for Occidental Petroleum Corp., the rig's Los
Angeles-based owners.
   The crew boarded the rig at dawn Sunday, but was forced off by
bad weather and a surge of flames from one of its wells, said the
spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with British custom.
   Divers and rescue crews will not be sent to search for the
bodies of the 149 missing men until after the debris is cleared and
Adair has capped leaking wells, Occidental executive John Brading
told a news conference Saturday.
   The Occidental spokesman said a small oil slick was reported
early Sunday, extending about 2 miles beyond the rig. Four
anti-pollution ships, equipped with spraying equipment, are
stationed near the platform, he said.
</TEXT>
