<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Fires     07-10 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fires,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forest Fire Dies Down, Parts Of Custer State Park Reopened</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET BROKAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CUSTER, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters on Sunday brought under control
a 17,000-acre forest fire that had burned within 3{ miles of Mount
Rushmore National Memorial and forced the evacuation of 1,000
people.
   Meanwhile, three wildfires in Southern California burned over
400 acres and caused $50,000 damage to a condominium but
authorities reported no injuries.
   The fire in South Dakota's Custer State Park, which was believed
to have been caused by lightning last Monday, was declared under
control at 6 p.m. Sunday, officials said.
   About 60 percent of the park was reopened earlier Sunday and
visitors began to return after crews contained the blaze's spread
the day before.
   All main roads in the park were to be reopened Monday morning,
said fire information officer Richard Homann.
   The blaze scorched the northern part of the 73,000-acre state
park and a small portion of the adjacent U.S. Forest Service land
that surrounds Mount Rushmore.
   Thirty-five firefighting crews of 20 persons each were sent home
Sunday, while two crews remained to assist in mop-up operations,
which are expected to take one to two weeks, Homann said.
   The fire was contained Saturday after thundershowers sprinkled
the area with about a quarter inch of rain, said fire information
officer Lynn Young. Lightning from the storms started nine
additional fires in the area, but local firefighters handled them,,
he said.
   ``It's enough to keep us a little nervous, but we haven't got a
big one going,'' Young said.
   ``We're just getting lots of phone calls. People just want to
get into the park, and we want them to do that as soon as it's
safe,'' Young said.
   In California, a wildfire charred 300 acres in the San
Bernardino National Forest Sunday, closing a 10-mile stretch of
Highway 74.
   About 250 firefighters surrounded the fire, which broke out late
in the morning and burned in a mountain area without any
structures, said Joanne Evans, a fire spokeswoman for the Riverside
County-California Department of Foresty.
   A separate brush fire broke out Sunday afternoon and burned 100
acres near the San Antonio Dam in Los Angeles County. About 100
county firefighters had the blaze 70 percent under control by
evening, said fireman Al Smith.
   A small brush fire in Newport Beach caused an estimated $50,000
damage to a condominium before firefighters brought the blaze under
control Sunday afternoon, said fire dispatcher Mary Ann Krumweide.
</TEXT>
