<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FrozenDelivery Bjt   07-10 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Frozen Delivery, Bjt,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ding-Dong _ Chicken Cordon Bleu And Espresso Mousse Balls Calling</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Combine the sales approaches of the Sears
catalog, a Tupperware party and the Avon lady, throw in frozen
ribs, cheesecake and other dishes and you have Sundborn Ltd.,
purveyor of home-delivered meals to time-starved consumers.
   Secaucus-based Sundborn, displays its culinary wares in a
catalog distributed at home food-tasting parties, and provides
delivery within 24 hours of upscale, frozen dishes _ the ribs go
for $28 and the cheesecake for $11.
   ``Gourmet food consultants'' host the tasting parties and give
catalogs to their friends and neighbors, collecting an average 12
percent commission on any orders. A customer's call to a toll-free
800 number brings dinner to the doorstep.
   Sundborn is ``an idea that grew out of my feeling that people
today had a poverty of time,'' said founder Richard LaMotta, who
also created the Chipwich ice cream sandwich.
   LaMotta thinks he found a market niche by combining the
attraction of home delivery and direct catalog sales.
   ``We're a substitute for going out to eat or getting pizza or
Chinese food,'' he said.
   The 170-item catalog features dishes gathered from regions and
restaurant menus around the nation, including cassoulet at $4.95,
Cajun catfish at $7.95, John Willingham's World Famous Ribs at $28
and Plaza Sweets Chocolate Velvet Boule at $15.
   LaMotta's food delivery idea is part of a nationwide trend,
industry experts say.
   ``I would guess that we're going to see more of these things,''
said Julie Mautner, an associate editor at Des Plaines, Ill.-based
Restaurant & Institutions magazine, a food-service trade
publication.
   She points to other companies emerging in the food delivery
field, such as General Mills' Order Inn division, which delivers
frozen dishes to three Minneapolis suburbs.
   Chicago-based Room Service arranges deliveries from area
restaurants to customers, and will even have tuxedo-clad waiters
set and clear the customer's table for an extra charge.
   Several chicken chains, including Popeye's and Kentucky Fried
Chicken, have experimented in home delivery, said William Trainer,
a restaurant analyst at Merrill Lynch & Co. in New York.
   ``People just don't have the time, but they want to eat well,''
said LaMotta _ well enough for Sundborn to sell about $250,000
worth of food in the past two months.
   One food industry colleague liked the idea, but was skeptical of
its merit.
   John Licari Jr., owner of Casa di Pizza in Bloomfield, said he
liked the idea but was skeptical of its merit.
   ``You're better off ordering a pizza,'' said Licari. ``It's got
everything there you need.''
   Nevertheless, Licari said his wife signed up as a Sundborn
consultant.
   ``I tried the food. It was pretty good. Me myself, personally,
I'd cook it, 'cause I'm in the business,'' he said.
   Sundborn, a subsidiary of Chipwich Inc., is losing money but
LaMotta hopes to see a profit and $30 million to $60 million in
sales within three years. It began delivery from its Totowa
distribution center in mid-April, two California franchises are
expected to open within two months and LaMotta said he plans to
have nationwide distribution within a year.
   Customers must buy a $50 minimum of the frozen goods _ which can
be heated in a conventional or microwave oven. The food can be
delivered in 24 hours within 50 miles of a distribution center or
in 48 hours outside of that radius.
   Sundborn's distribution centers are stocked by specialty food
manufacturers that generally supply restaurants, LaMotta said.
   Sundborn may sound like a yuppie service, but LaMotta rejects
the label. However, he concedes his clientele is not a
``coupon-clipping'' discount supermarket crowd.
   ``It goes beyond yuppies, though,'' he said. ``It really is the
ultimate busy person's food service.''
</TEXT>
