<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MGMSale     07-10 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MGM Sale,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Expected To Sell Pictures Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Pictures unit of
MGM-UA Communications Co. is expected to be sold along with its
famous lion logo to investor Kirk Kerkorian and another group, a
newspaper reported Sunday.
   Under the deal, investor Burt Sugarman and movie producers Jon
Peters and Peter Guber would acquire 25 percent of the pictures
unit, the Los Angeles Times said.
   Kerkorian, who owns an 82 percent stake in the unit's parent
MGM-UA, is expected to buy the balance of the pictures unit after
first offering shares of it to stockholders in the parent company,
the newspaper said.
   Other details of the deal were not reported and apparently still
were being worked out over the weekend. An announcement was
expected as early as Monday, the newspaper said.
   Lee Rich, chairman of MGM-UA, could not be reached for comment.
   MGM-UA, which produced the movie ``Moonstruck'' and the TV
series ``thirtysomething,'' had indicated previously it would
consider offers for all or part of the studio.
   The expected pictures unit sale apparently will include MGM's
famous Leo the Lion logo and its movie and TV production unit.
   MGM-UA shareholders apparently would continue controlling the
studio's United Artists unit and its 950-film library, which
includes the ``Rocky'' and ``Pink Panther'' films.
   Kerkorian reportedly had been asking about $200 million for the
MGM unit and about $1 billion for the whole company.
   Despite some successes, MGM has been plagued by losses which
amounted to $10.8 million for the nine months ended May 31. That
was down from $41.9 million in the same period a year earlier.
   MGM-UA stock closed at $15.75 a share on Friday, up 87{ cents in
New York Stock Exchange trading. Based on the company's 50 million
outstanding common shares, MGM-UA has a market value of $787.5
million.
   Sugarman became associated with Peters and Guber last year when
his Barris Industries merged with a private independent movie
production company owned by the two producers.
   Barris Industries, a TV production and syndication company, is
best known for ``The New Newlywed Game'' and ``The All New Dating
Game.''
   Guber and Peters' films include ``The Witches of Eastwick,''
with Jack Nicholson and ``The Color Purple,'' starring Whoopi
Goldberg.
</TEXT>
