<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GTECH-China     07-10 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GTECH-China,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GTECH Goes After Lottery Market In China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GTECH Corp., the world's leading maker
of computerized lottery systems, has its eyes set on the world's
biggest market: China.
   The company is negotiating a contract to set up ticket-printing
plants in China, a deal that executives hope eventually leads to
the installation of an on-line lottery network similar to those
used in the United States.
   The winner of the contract to print tickets for China's handful
of paper lottery games could have the inside track on any future
projects, said Guy B. Snowden, GTECH chairman.
   ``One thing that I've found out about Asian philosophy and
Chinese culture in particular is that if you get going with them,
the relationships tend to be very long term,'' Snowden said.
   Iit has been known since last fall, when Chinese representatives
attended a lottery industry exposition, that the nation was
interested in a more sophisticated lottery.
   Lottery company executives say China's 1 billion population and
its increasingly consumerized society make it a tempting target.
   About a year ago, China introduced lotteries in a handful of
provinces. Buses drive to villages and sell tickets from a window _
tickets that GTECH hopes to win the contract to print.
   A computerized on-line lottery system like those in use in the
United States could follow, Snowden said. ``We want to provide them
an electronic bus,'' he said.
   China is the largest, but not the only, country where GTECH and
other lottery-system makers are seeking to expand.
   Lottery company executives estimate the world could easily
support 250,000 wagering terminals, yet only 60,000 have been
installed. In the United States, by contrast, the competition for
lottery contracts has dwindled; fewer states are starting lotteries
and most that already have them are under long-term contracts.
   GTECH reportedly is close to contracts in South Korea, Turkey,
Taiwan and West Germany, and runs on-line lotteries in Australia,
Canada, Iceland, Ireland, Mexico, New Zealand, Spain, Singapore,
Sweden and Venezuela, as well as in 10 American states.
</TEXT>
