<1ST_LINE>u f AM-DroughtRdp 1stLd-Writethru f0012 07-10 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0012,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scattered Rain Doesn't Alleviate Drought</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Des Moines...', UPDATE with more rain detail;
SUBS and high temperatures, picking up at the 9th graf pvs, `Heat
has...'. INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th graf, `Rain also...', to add
detail on heat records in East, picking up 9th graf pvs, `Heat
has...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain was scattered across sections of the Plains and upper Great
Lakes on Sunday, but not enough to cancel the drought, and one
Kentucky utility said stricter water conservation may be needed.
   Kentucky Gov. Wallace Wilkinson has called a special water
emergency meeting for Monday to discuss with local government
officials the severity of the drought and what action the state
plans to take.
   Showers and thunderstorms with mostly light rain were scattered
along a cold front that extended from the upper Great Lakes into
the central Plains early Sunday.
   Des Moines, Iowa, picked up 2.31 inches of rain in the 24 hours
up to 7 a.m., but that left the city still 7 inches below normal so
far this year, the National Weather Service said. Lansing in
northeasten Iowa got 3.85 inches.
   Parts of Kansas also got a fair amount of rain with 3.39 inches
in 24 hours at Madison, and 2.20 inches at Blue Rapids, the weather
service said.
   Up to three-quarters of an inch fell on parts of Kentucky during
the weekend.
   ``Every little bit helps, but what we need is a real soaking of
a couple of inches or more,'' weather service meteorologist Marilyn
Scholz said Sunday in Louisville. ``We need several of this kind of
(weather) system to really get us back ... and break the drought.''
   Rain also was scattered over parts of Michigan on Sunday, but
one corn and soybean farmer from the state's Thumb area wasn't
impressed. ``We're just getting a little spitting here and there, a
few raindrops on the road,'' said Gary O'Connor of Jeddo, about 10
miles northwest of Port Huron.
   Thunderstorms also spread from Michigan into Indiana and Ohio.
   Temperatures soared above 90 in the East, reaching 100 at
Washington and 98 at New York City, the weather service said.
Baltimore's airport hit a record 100 and Roanoke, Va., reached a
record 96. The record of 95 was tied at Buffalo, N.Y., for the
city's seventh straight record day.
   Above-90 readings had people flocking to the seaside in Boston,
according to a spokesman for a state agency that polices the
beaches. ``It's crowded, very crowded,'' said Metropolitan District
Commission police Sgt. Edward F. Stanley. ``There's no parking
available, and the people are all over each other.''
   Heat has combined with the drought in many areas to increase
demand for water.
   A ban on ``non-essential'' water use may be recommended this
week in Lexington, Ky., according to Robert Edens, vice president
and general manager with the Kentucky-American Water Co.
   On Friday the company pumped 45.9 million gallons of water, up
slightly from Thursday's 45.6 million gallons. The company has
targeted 44 million gallons as an acceptable rate of daily use.
   Despite the drought, entries in the livestock and crop shows at
the Ohio State Fair during Aug. 4-21 in Columbus are running close
to last year's record, said Jim D. Goard, the fair's director of
agriculture and livestock.
   ``I think people want to get away from home and forget their
problems. It gets depressing out there. Going to the fair lifts you
up,'' Goard said.
   The heat wave in the Midwest has raised the tempers of public
housing residents in Cleveland, and some residents of Cedar
Extension Estate challenged the Cuyahoga Metropolitan Housing
Authority to provide air conditioners for health reasons or face a
rent strike.
   ``The Cedar building is filled with elderly, handicapped and
frail people whose health is being threatened by the hottest
weather in a half-century,'' said Frank J. Kidd Jr., president of
the Central Advisory Council, a group of tenant representatives.
   The drought also has heightened the danger of fires.
   In Michigan's north-central Lower Peninsula, about 200 residents
around Clear Lake had returned home Sunday after a fire in the Au
Sable State Forest consumed about 400 acres the day before, said
Cindy Hobart, a dispatcher with the Ogemaw County Sheriff's
Department.
</TEXT>
